01:07:35.850 --> 01:07:37.150
I'm not sure.

01:07:37.150 --> 01:07:38.450
And then Sakyamuni the second.

01:07:38.450 --> 01:07:44.450
But there's another point about
that which I didn't mention.

01:07:44.450 --> 01:07:48.310
I talked about that
list in the Mahavastu

01:07:48.310 --> 01:07:54.640
of 331,140,263 buddhas.

01:07:54.640 --> 01:08:01.250
What I didn't say is that out of
the 300 million, out of the 331,

01:08:01.250 --> 01:08:03.600
300 million were
named Sakyamuni.

01:08:03.600 --> 01:08:06.880
And according to that
text, there was a stretch

01:08:06.880 --> 01:08:13.610
of 30 million buddhas in a row
that were all had the same name.

01:08:13.610 --> 01:08:18.950
And I have thought about and
failed to understand what that,

01:08:18.950 --> 01:08:21.510
why that is and what that means.

01:08:21.510 --> 01:08:27.390
But there is -- You know,
buddhas are and by impression,

01:08:27.390 --> 01:08:31.050
they're more or less the
same and their images,

01:08:31.050 --> 01:08:35.500
I don't think I have one
here, but you see in Gandhari

01:08:35.500 --> 01:08:38.750
and other sculptures,
you see sets of buddhas

01:08:38.750 --> 01:08:41.400
like the seven buddhas or
sometimes eight buddhas

01:08:41.400 --> 01:08:44.410
and they're all almost
exactly the same.

01:08:44.410 --> 01:08:48.450
So there seems to be a
range of possibilities

01:08:48.450 --> 01:08:52.320
that buddhas are always similar
and they can be very similar

01:08:52.320 --> 01:08:55.590
and sometimes they are
absolutely identical.

01:08:55.590 --> 01:08:57.240
But I'm still pondering that.

01:08:57.240 --> 01:08:59.950
It is hard to understand that.

01:09:05.850 --> 01:09:07.650
Yes, sir?

01:09:07.650 --> 01:09:27.690
[ Inaudible Audience Question ]

01:09:27.690 --> 01:09:31.850
Yes. It's hard to
give exact numbers.

01:09:31.850 --> 01:09:37.660
Let me explain the problem.

01:09:37.660 --> 01:09:41.350
There are groups of manuscripts.

01:09:41.350 --> 01:09:45.490
There are six or
seven major groups.

01:09:45.490 --> 01:09:50.230
And typically, one of these
groups will typically have,

01:09:50.230 --> 01:09:53.660
take two or three
dozen manuscripts

01:09:53.660 --> 01:09:56.590
but there's one group
which comes

01:09:56.590 --> 01:09:59.580
from a place called Bamiyan,
which people have heard

01:09:59.580 --> 01:10:02.530
of because they were, everybody
knows they were giant buddhas

01:10:02.530 --> 01:10:08.890
and the Taliban blew them up
in 1999 or whenever it was.

01:10:08.890 --> 01:10:12.310
What the public general
doesn't know is

01:10:12.310 --> 01:10:14.230
that they were also
thousands and thousands

01:10:14.230 --> 01:10:17.870
of manuscripts found there.

01:10:17.870 --> 01:10:23.300
And most of those manuscripts
were later manuscripts

01:10:23.300 --> 01:10:25.980
in Sanskrit but there's
an early phase

01:10:25.980 --> 01:10:33.400
of Gandhari manuscripts similar
to what I've been talking about.

01:10:33.400 --> 01:10:40.480
Now that contains -- That
consists of 300 or so fragments

01:10:40.480 --> 01:10:44.030
and most of them are -- When I
say fragments, I mean like this.

01:10:44.030 --> 01:10:46.730
So it's very hard to
say, okay, what is that?

01:10:46.730 --> 01:10:50.260
Is that 300 manuscripts
or are they part

01:10:50.260 --> 01:10:55.500
and how many manuscripts
were they actually parts of

01:10:55.500 --> 01:10:56.800
and in most cases they're

01:10:56.800 --> 01:11:00.470
so small that's it's
hard to be sure.

01:11:00.470 --> 01:11:05.630
So there might be 300 fragments
but there might've been 50

01:11:05.630 --> 01:11:10.430
or 60 manuscripts at a
little more than a guess.

01:11:10.430 --> 01:11:12.650
So that's why the
numbers are very fuzzy

01:11:12.650 --> 01:11:14.580
and that's why I've
been a little bit vague.

01:11:14.580 --> 01:11:20.470
But I would say we have
-- Well, I said 200 --

01:11:20.470 --> 01:11:24.710
We have partial remnants
of at least 200 manuscripts

01:11:24.710 --> 01:11:27.330
and we have possibly
more than that.

01:11:27.330 --> 01:11:31.380
In terms of complete manuscripts
or texts that are complete

01:11:31.380 --> 01:11:37.190
or more or less complete,
you know, say 90%,

01:11:37.190 --> 01:11:41.290
very few, maybe three or four.

01:11:41.290 --> 01:11:45.300
This thing, I think I actually
calculated, I don't remember.

01:11:45.300 --> 01:11:50.800
We have maybe 75 to 80%
of the original of this

01:11:50.800 --> 01:11:53.900
and that's much, much
better than usual.

01:11:53.900 --> 01:11:56.800
So it's a little hard to
say exactly how much we have

01:11:56.800 --> 01:12:02.620
but we do have a lot of
material, enough to really begin

01:12:02.620 --> 01:12:06.750
to get a glimpse
of the big picture.

01:12:06.750 --> 01:12:08.550
Yes, please.

01:12:08.550 --> 01:12:24.600
[ Inaudible Audience Question ]

01:12:24.600 --> 01:12:31.040
The answer is almost
all are Buddhist texts,

01:12:31.040 --> 01:12:35.950
not necessarily sutras
but Buddhist texts

01:12:35.950 --> 01:12:41.740
of any kind clearly
Buddhist content.

01:12:41.740 --> 01:12:49.000
Sorry, I broke your microphone.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:53.690
There are two exceptions
in all of these 200

01:12:53.690 --> 01:12:56.120
or whatever manuscripts,
there are two exceptions

01:12:56.120 --> 01:12:58.030
but they're really interesting.

01:12:58.030 --> 01:13:01.590
One of them is a kind
of legal document.

01:13:01.590 --> 01:13:06.370
The other, which was just
discovered very recently and is

01:13:06.370 --> 01:13:07.670
about to be published

01:13:07.670 --> 01:13:10.440
by my colleague Mark
Allen [assumed spelling],

01:13:10.440 --> 01:13:13.860
you might know who he is.

01:13:13.860 --> 01:13:18.760
And it's actually
just little fragments

01:13:18.760 --> 01:13:23.230
of what would've been a very
interesting text but it's enough

01:13:23.230 --> 01:13:24.530
to see what's going on.

01:13:24.530 --> 01:13:29.940
It's actually a record of the
monastery's record of donations.

01:13:29.940 --> 01:13:35.720
And not only that, it lists
the names of the donors

01:13:35.720 --> 01:13:41.090
and the primary donor
was [inaudible],

01:13:41.090 --> 01:13:48.300
who's a well-known figure in
Indian history of around 100 AD.

01:13:48.300 --> 01:13:52.000
So this is really a great thing
for us because it clarifies

01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:57.070
and confirms the historical
context within that period

01:13:57.070 --> 01:14:00.330
that I talked about, that
so-called foreign ruler period,

01:14:00.330 --> 01:14:07.390
and he was previously known but
[inaudible] his relationship

01:14:07.390 --> 01:14:10.530
to Buddhism was not
clear and now we have it.

01:14:10.530 --> 01:14:15.280
He was mentioned several
times in this text.

01:14:15.280 --> 01:14:19.110
So it's not a Buddhist text in
the sense that the others are

01:14:19.110 --> 01:14:23.680
but it's monastic business
and it's a real eyeopener.

01:14:23.680 --> 01:14:26.880
And this is going to be
published in a few months.

01:14:26.880 --> 01:14:29.380
So really change the picture.

01:14:29.380 --> 01:14:34.790
But that's all we have
so far of that type.

